I. REVIEW OF KEY ECHR ARTICLES

Article 5 ECHR - Right to Liberty and Security

**General Rule:** Everyone has the right to liberty and security. State
CANNOT deprive liberty except in specific situations listed in Article
5(1).

Key Exception: Article 5(1)(c)

-   Arrest and pretrial detention for bringing before competent legal
    authority

-   Exceptions are exhaustive (closed list) and interpreted strictly

Article 5(3) - Promptness Requirement

**Rule:** When arrested, person must be brought *\"promptly\"* before a
judge

> **ðŸ“Œ Brogan and Others v. UK:** \"Promptly\" means approximately 4
> DAYS maximum. Even terrorism cases don\'t justify longer periods
> without judicial oversight.

-   [x] Within 4 days = generally acceptable

-   âœ— Beyond 4 days = likely violation

-   **Purpose:** Prevents arbitrary detention and ensures judicial
    oversight quickly

Article 5(3) - Reasonable Time for Trial

**Rule:** Once detained pretrial, person has right to trial within
reasonable time OR release pending trial

> **ðŸ“Œ Letellier v. France:** \"Reasonable time\" depends on
> case-by-case assessment considering complexity and seriousness.

-   Simple shoplifting â†’ shorter time required

-   Complex financial fraud â†’ longer time acceptable

Article 8 ECHR - Right to Privacy

**Article 8(1):** Everyone has the right to respect for private and
family life, home, and correspondence.

**Article 8(2):** State can interfere IF:

1.  **In accordance with law** (accessible, foreseeable, sufficient
    quality)

2.  **For legitimate aim** (public safety, prevention of crime, etc.)

3.  **Proportionate/necessary**

> **ðŸ“Œ Niemietz v. Germany:**

-   \"Home\" interpreted broadly â†’ includes business premises,
    > professional offices

-   \"Correspondence\" includes emails, phone communications

-   Any search must be proportionate

> **ðŸ“Œ Klass v. Germany:** Law must be of \"sufficient quality\" with
> clear provisions, safeguards against abuse, and independent oversight.

Privilege Against Self-Incrimination

**Core Principle:** Cannot be forced to provide evidence against
yourself (part of Article 6 fair trial rights)

Two Categories of Evidence

**[1. Evidence Depending on Will of Accused]{.underline}**

-   **PROTECTED** by privilege

-   Examples: Spoken statements, written confessions, testimony

-   Cannot be compelled

**[2. Evidence with Independent Existence]{.underline}**

-   **Generally NOT PROTECTED**

-   Examples: DNA samples, blood samples, fingerprints

-   Rationale: Exists independently of your will

âš ï¸ CRITICAL EXCEPTION: Jalloh v. Germany

> **JALLOH RULE:** When evidence is inside the body and extracting it
> violates Article 3 (inhuman/degrading treatment), the privilege
> against self-incrimination DOES apply.

-   **Facts:** Police forcibly administered emetic to make suspect vomit
    drugs

-   **Holdings:**

    -   Article 3 violation (inhuman/degrading treatment)

    -   Article 6 violation (privilege applies despite \"independent
        existence\")

-   **Exam distinction:**

    -   [x] DNA swab with consent/minor compulsion = acceptable

    -   âœ— Forcing emetic/stomach pumping = violates both Articles 3 & 6

Functional Equivalent: Allan v. UK

> **ALLAN PRINCIPLE:** State cannot circumvent procedural protections by
> using indirect methods (e.g., undercover cellmate to extract
> confession).

-   **Facts:** Police planted fake cellmate after suspect invoked right
    to silence

-   **Holding:** This is \"functional equivalent of police
    interrogation\" â†’ same protections apply

-   State can\'t avoid giving Miranda-type warnings through deceptive
    methods

II\. PUBLIC PROSECUTION SERVICE

The \"Gatekeepers\" Role

**Definition:** Prosecutors are the link between police and court. They
decide whether criminal prosecution takes place and bring cases to
court.

-   **Why \"gatekeepers\"?** They hold the key to the courtroom door

-   They decide who gets prosecuted

-   Without prosecutor\'s decision to prosecute â†’ no trial, no
    conviction possible

Why This Power is Crucial

> **KEY INSIGHT:** The decision to prosecute is arguably MORE powerful
> than the judge\'s sentencing decision, because without prosecution,
> there is no case at all.

Fascinating Comparative Aspect

**How prosecutorial power is organized tells you about:**

-   History and culture of the legal system

-   Trust/confidence in state institutions

-   Balance between individual rights and state power

*Examples:*

-   Netherlands: Prosecutors have substantial power

-   Other countries: Prosecutorial power kept to minimum

